{% extends "base.html.twig" %}
{% block title %}Slim Framework with Bootstrap{% endblock %}
{% block container %}
    <section>
        <h1>Welcome to Slim With Bootstrap!</h1>

        <p>
            I assume that this is not your first Slim application; if that assumption is false, you should probably
            start here: <a href="http://docs.slimframework.com/#Hello-World" target="_blank">"Hello World" Tutorial</a>,
            then come on back to this project. </p>

        <p>
            If you don't actually intend to use Bootstrap 3 for your project, then
            <a href="https://github.com/codeguy/Slim-Skeleton">Slim Skeleton</a> is probably a better fit for your
            needs.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>The Goods</h2>

        <p>A base template with a sticky header and footer is provided for all pages to extend.</p>

        <p>It can be found in: <code>templates/base.html.twig</code></p>

        <p>Simply begin all of your page templates with this line:
            <code>{{ '{%' }} extends "base.html.twig" {{ '%}' }}</code>
        </p>

        <h3>Provided Blocks</h3>

        <p>The following blocks are provided: </p>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block container %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            Implement this block to render all of your page content within a single
            <code>&lt;div class="container"&gt;</code> element.<br>
            This is good if none of your content needs to 'bleed' outside of the container width.
        </blockquote>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block content %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            Implement this block if you need some of your elements to 'bleed' outside the container.<br>
            For example, if you want to use a carousel widget with navigation arrows that render outside the container.<br>
            You will need to implement your own <code>&lt;div class="container"&gt;</code> elements.<br>
        </blockquote>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block title %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            This sets the page title. Plain text-only, no html elements needed.
        </blockquote>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block description %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            This sets the page description. Plain text-only, no html elements needed.
        </blockquote>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block meta %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            This sets additional meta-data within the header. Wrapper elemets are required as we don't know what you're
            going to set.<br>
            Example: <code>&lt;meta property="og:image" content="http://ia.media-imdb.com/images/rock.jpg" /&gt;</code>
        </blockquote>
        <h4><code>{{ '{% block scripts %}' }}</code></h4>
        <blockquote>
            Put any page-specific javascript blocks or includes in this block;<br>
            it will be rendered at the end of the page, after jQuery, Bootstrap, and app.js
        </blockquote>

    </section>
{% endblock %}